---930844984-1889430779-1012852482=:25560
Content-Type: MESSAGE/RFC822; CHARSET=US-ASCII
Content-ID: <Pine.LNX.4.33.0202041353572.25560@ocilap5.ociweb.com>
Content-Description: Re: Security_PolicyFactory updates and 'any' operators for locals (fwd)

Date: Fri, 1 Feb 2002 15:09:10 -0600 (CST)
From: Chris Cleeland <cleeland@ociweb.com>
To: Ossama Othman <ossama@doc.ece.uci.edu>
cc:  <parsons@cs.wustl.edu>, Tom Venturella <venturella_t@ociweb.com>
Subject: Re: Security_PolicyFactory updates and 'any' operators for locals
In-Reply-To: <20020201205957.GB26656@doc.ece.uci.edu>
Message-ID: <Pine.LNX.4.33.0202011505260.25560-100000@ocilap5.ociweb.com>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII


On Fri, 1 Feb 2002, Ossama Othman wrote:

> > Seems that the IDL compiler doesn't generate 'any' insertion operators for a
> > local interface.  I've tried to find documentation to that effect in a spec
> > somewhere, but haven't been able to locate it.  Can that be right?!
>
> Doh!  A "local" interface is locality constrained so it cannot be
> marshalled into another format (e.g. CDR).  However, I don't know if
> that precludes it from being inserted into an Any.

I actually checked the text of the 2.4.2 spec and the only thing that it says
about regarding a local interface and an any is this:

"Local types cannot be marshaled and references to local objects cannot be
converted to strings. Any attempt to marshal a local object, such as via an
unconstrained base interface, as an Object, or as the contents of an any, or
to pass a local object to ORB::object_to_string, shall result in a MARSHAL
system exception with OMG minor code 2."

This implies that it *can* be part of an any.  Jeff, can you advise us on why
the any insertion operators aren't generated for a local interface?

> > Also, Ossama, we noticed that the Security_PolicyFactory::create_policy
> > doesn't seem to do anything at all with the SecInvocationsCredentialsPolicy.
> > I presume that's an oversight and I'm happy to fix that,
>
> Yep.  Big oversight on my part.  I could have sworn that I added the
> necessary code.  I guess not.  :-)

Yep:-)

> > but is it really as
> > simple as mimicking the code that's in there for the other policies?
>
> Yep.  No brainer.

Of course, the code won't compile at this point since we don't have any
insertion/extraction operators.

I guess one possible workaround (for now) is to remove the locality
constraint from Credentials.  That means that we need more caution in the
code, but it would at least let us continue working.

-cj

-- 
