Hi Chris,

On Fri, Feb 01, 2002 at 03:09:10PM -0600, Chris Cleeland wrote:
> "Local types cannot be marshaled and references to local objects cannot be
> converted to strings. Any attempt to marshal a local object, such as via an
> unconstrained base interface, as an Object, or as the contents of an any, or
> to pass a local object to ORB::object_to_string, shall result in a MARSHAL
> system exception with OMG minor code 2."

The CCM spec says minor code 4.  Why can't specs live together in
peace?:-)

In any case, TAO adheres to this part of the spec, including throwing
the appropriate exception.

> This implies that it *can* be part of an any.  Jeff, can you advise us on why
> the any insertion operators aren't generated for a local interface?

BTW, it would really suck if the spec did indeed disallow this since
there would be no way to portably initialize a
SecurityLevel2::InvocationCredentialsPolicy policy.

> I guess one possible workaround (for now) is to remove the locality
> constraint from Credentials.  That means that we need more caution in the
> code, but it would at least let us continue working.

Yuck!  I guess that we don't have a choice, unless of course we're
missing something really fundamental about initializing a policy that
contains locality-constrained objects.

-Ossama
-- 
