Hi,


> > > Seems that the IDL compiler doesn't generate 'any' insertion 
> operators for a
> > > local interface.  I've tried to find documentation to that effect in 
> a spec
> > > somewhere, but haven't been able to locate it.  Can that be right?!
> >
> > Doh!  A "local" interface is locality constrained so it cannot be
> > marshalled into another format (e.g. CDR).  However, I don't know if
> > that precludes it from being inserted into an Any.
>
>I actually checked the text of the 2.4.2 spec and the only thing that it says
>about regarding a local interface and an any is this:
>
>"Local types cannot be marshaled and references to local objects cannot be
>converted to strings. Any attempt to marshal a local object, such as via an
>unconstrained base interface, as an Object, or as the contents of an any, or
>to pass a local object to ORB::object_to_string, shall result in a MARSHAL
>system exception with OMG minor code 2."
>
>This implies that it *can* be part of an any.  Jeff, can you advise us on why
>the any insertion operators aren't generated for a local interface?

Our implementation of Any operators uses the CDR operators. To generate
the Any operators for local interfaces, we would have to also generate the
CDR operators. I guess it seemed like it would be tough to always throw
that MARSHAL exception with the CDR operators there.
However, it looks like they're going to have to get generated, and some kind
of way to prevent someone from marshaling a local interface will have to be
found.

In the case where a local interface is marshaled inside an Any, I don't think
it would be too bad -- we could check the typecode inside the Any << operator.
Not sure about the case where we marshal a bare local interface though. How
do you tell whether you're using the CDR operator to marshal it or to put it
into an Any?


Jeff

