On Fri, 1 Feb 2002, Ossama Othman wrote:

> On Fri, Feb 01, 2002 at 09:43:38PM -0600, Chris Cleeland wrote:
> > No, I interpret it differently.  What the spec is saying (and, btw, the 2.4.2
> > spec had the same thing in it that you put in, Ossama) is that, if you try to
> > marshal an any which contains a local interface, then you're out of luck.
> >
> > If you accept that interpretation, then it should be okay to insert a local
> > interface into an any; just don't try to pass it across the wire.
>
> Yes, I like your interpretation, especially since it is more useful.
> ;-)

<yoda>like YOUR interpretation better, do I.  More useful...it is!</yoda>

> So it seems that we've found a bug in TAO.  Yes?

Yes.  I'm not sure what to do about the CDR thing, Jeff.  I started hacking
on the IDL compiler and ran into that this evening.  Seems that what we'd
have to do is somehow mark the CDR stream as "blessed" to hold a local.  If
we mark the stream, we'll also be able to easily detect that an any is
holding a local without interpreting the type.

Would that work?  Or is there a better way to solve this problem?


