Hi guys,

On Mon, Feb 04, 2002 at 10:39:46AM -0600, Chris Cleeland wrote:
> On Mon, 4 Feb 2002, Jeff Parsons wrote:
> 
> > >Would that work?  Or is there a better way to solve this problem?
> >
> > Here's an approach that I though of over the weekend, while I was practicing
> > my couch potato act ;-).
> >
> > CDR operators for non-local interfaces just call the ones for CORBA::Object.

BTW, I finally learned what the "proper" term is for non-locality
constrained interfaces after running through some specs this past
weekend.  You'd never guess...  "unconstrained interfaces."  Who'd of
thunk?:)

> Sounds interesting.  I really like the idea of not marshalling at all,
> though; I mean, it can't go over the wire, so why even bother marshalling?
> We could instead just hold a copy of the object in native form, right?  Seems
> that might work better for performance.  For that matter, couldn't you apply
> the same thing to non-local objects, and only do the marshalling when the any
                    ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
"Unconstrained objects."  :-)

> itself gets marshalled?  That might make 'any' operations less costly (then
> again, maybe not).

It would, particularly if the Any is never sent over the wire.
Insertion and extraction would be "wicked" fast.  :-)  Memory
requirements would be less since there would be no need to marshal the
value into a CDR stream until sending it over the wire.  I know that
this has been suggested in the past but I seem to recall that this
wasn't as easy as it seemed.  Jeff?

> into the OCI repository?

-Ossama

