Hi Chris,

On Mon, Feb 04, 2002 at 11:17:30AM -0600, Chris Cleeland wrote:
> On Mon, 4 Feb 2002, Ossama Othman wrote:
> > BTW, I finally learned what the "proper" term is for non-locality
> > constrained interfaces after running through some specs this past
> > weekend.  You'd never guess...  "unconstrained interfaces."  Who'd of
> > thunk?:)
> 
> Ooooo...where'd you dig up *that* nugget?

Section 3.7.6.1 (Local Interface Semantics) in the CORBA 2.6 spec:

-------
An interface declaration containing the keyword local declares a local
interface.  An interface declaration not containing the keyword local
is referred to as an unconstrained interface. An object implementing a
local interfaces is referred to as a local object.
-------

It's nice to know this since I always came up with my own make-shift
terms in the past.  :-)

> > It would, particularly if the Any is never sent over the wire.
> > Insertion and extraction would be "wicked" fast.  :-)
> 
> "wicked"...you from Boston now or something?  Been watching some Patriot
> fans' celebrations on all-night TV?

Is that a Boston thing?  I didn't know that.  I just was just trying
to be "cool."  :-)

> BTW, I'm in the process of redoing the SecurityLevel2 interface to be, eh,
> "unconstrained interfaces",

Knowledge is power!

> at least the ones that have to get stuffed into
> any's.  Another alternative is to provide a hack method that allows one to
> create the policy object WITHOUT going through the policy factory and, thus,
> not requiring one to shove the Credentials into an 'any'.  I'm not sure how
> easy this would be, though, and it would be really icky in the long term.
> 
> One thing I don't like about making Credentials unconstrained is that
> somebody could then conceivably pass it across the wire.  Can anybody think
> of a way that I could easily prevent that, even if it means going in and
> temporarily hacking the generated code (there is precedence for that, at
> least)?

The implementation would still inherit from CORBA::LocalObject.  That
would prevent object_to_string() from working, but I'm not sure about
the CDR stream insertion operator.

-Ossama
-- 
Ossama Othman <ossama@ece.uci.edu>
Distributed Object Computing Laboratory, Univ. of California at Irvine
1024D/F7A394A8 - 84ED AA0B 1203 99E4 1068  70E6 5EB7 5E71 F7A3 94A8

