Hi,

> > >Would that work?  Or is there a better way to solve this problem?
> >
> > Here's an approach that I though of over the weekend, while I was 
> practicing
> > my couch potato act ;-).
> >
> > CDR operators for non-local interfaces just call the ones for 
> CORBA::Object.
> > What if we just put code like that inside the generated Any operators for
> > local interfaces. That way there would be no CDR operators generated for
> > local interfaces, and the question of marshaling one would be caught by the
> > compiler. Then in the CDR operators for Anys, we'd have to have a check
> > for the typecode kind being tk_local_interface, and throw the exception if
> > it is seen -- not a big deal to check since the Any would just be accessing
> > its own typecode member. Of course, we still have to generate a typecode
> > for local interfaces, but we would have to do in order to deal with Anys no
> > matter what approach is used.
> >
> > What say?
>
>Sounds interesting.  I really like the idea of not marshalling at all,
>though; I mean, it can't go over the wire, so why even bother marshalling?
>We could instead just hold a copy of the object in native form, right?  Seems
>that might work better for performance.  For that matter, couldn't you apply
>the same thing to non-local objects, and only do the marshalling when the any
>itself gets marshalled?  That might make 'any' operations less costly (then
>again, maybe not).

I like that idea for local interfaces -- just cast to and from void*, 
right? For
non-local interfaces, maybe, I'm not sure -- seems like it would hurt the
performance in the critical path, right where we want it to be optimal. But
I'll think about it some more.


>Your proposal definitely mirrors the way that things work now better.  And if
>it's easier to implement, then I say go for it.  Do you think you'll be able
>to keep it separate from other changes so that we can more easily fold it
>into the OCI repository?


I don't think it would be too bad. The Any extraction operator checks for type
equivalence with a call that uses the environment parameter, and that is now
different in the two repositories, but otherwise I don't see any conflicts. The
IDL compiler changes would just involve removing the 'local' guards for 
typecode
generation, and for Any operators, and adding the new code for
the Any operator implementation.

Jeff

