MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII


On Mon, 4 Feb 2002, Jeff Parsons wrote:

> >Sounds interesting.  I really like the idea of not marshalling at all,
> >though; I mean, it can't go over the wire, so why even bother marshalling?
> >We could instead just hold a copy of the object in native form, right?  Seems
> >that might work better for performance.  For that matter, couldn't you apply
> >the same thing to non-local objects, and only do the marshalling when the any
> >itself gets marshalled?  That might make 'any' operations less costly (then
> >again, maybe not).
>
> I like that idea for local interfaces -- just cast to and from void*,
> right?

Yup.  Just have to know what you're casting to/from, so you'd have to keep
that information around.

Do locality-constrained interfaces derive from CORBA::Object or from
CORBA::LocalObject?  I would hope that, ultimately, they'd derive from
Object, otherwise there'd be some major interface upheavals!

> For non-local interfaces, maybe, I'm not sure -- seems like it would hurt
> the performance in the critical path, right where we want it to be
> optimal. But I'll think about it some more.

Which path is the critical path in this case?  Making a remote invocation?

Seems that you'll spend the time marshalling one way or another, and it just
depends on when you want to pay for it.  You can do the "installment plan",
i.e., marshal into the any, then just copy that premarshalled stuff into the
CDR stream when/if the any hits the wire, or you can do a "lump sum payment"
where you marshal everything if/when the any hits the wire.  Or, am I missing
something (which is quite probable)?

> >Your proposal definitely mirrors the way that things work now better.  And if
> >it's easier to implement, then I say go for it.  Do you think you'll be able
> >to keep it separate from other changes so that we can more easily fold it
> >into the OCI repository?
>
>
> I don't think it would be too bad. The Any extraction operator checks for
> type equivalence with a call that uses the environment parameter, and
> that is now different in the two repositories, but otherwise I don't see
> any conflicts.

Actually, we're updating our repo today to use the ACE_ENV... arg macros
rather than TAO_ENV..., so after that, the macros will be identical.  Have
there been many IDL compiler changes since 1.2.1 got released?

> The IDL compiler changes would just involve removing the 'local' guards
> for typecode generation, and for Any operators,

And you know what I did on Friday?  I did most of that...

> and adding the new code for the Any operator implementation.

Didn't do this.

Wouldn't you also have to modify the 'any' implementation that hangs on to
the void*, or was that the "new code for the Any operator implementation"?

-cj

