User-Agent: Mutt/1.3.25i
X-AntiVirus: scanned for viruses by AMaViS 0.2.1 (http://amavis.org/)


Hi Chris,

On Mon, Feb 04, 2002 at 11:25:10AM -0600, Chris Cleeland wrote:
> Do locality-constrained interfaces derive from CORBA::Object or from
> CORBA::LocalObject?  I would hope that, ultimately, they'd derive from
> Object, otherwise there'd be some major interface upheavals!

Both.  Local object implementations must explicitly/manually inherit
from CORBA::LocalObject.  For example:

IDL:
	local interface Foo {};

C++:
	class Foo_i
	  : public virtual Foo,
	    public virtual CORBA::LocalObject
	{
	  //
	};

The Foo object inherits from CORBA::Object in the generated stub.

> > For non-local interfaces, maybe, I'm not sure -- seems like it would hurt
> > the performance in the critical path, right where we want it to be
> > optimal. But I'll think about it some more.

That's a good point.  Instead of pre-marshaling the value, we'd be
doing the actual marshaling in the critical path.  We could optimize
things so that the marshaling occurs once, but I guess that's still
expensive if the cost of that marsharling is greater than the
aggregate cost of a given number of remote method invocations.

> Actually, we're updating our repo today to use the ACE_ENV... arg macros
> rather than TAO_ENV..., so after that, the macros will be identical.  Have
> there been many IDL compiler changes since 1.2.1 got released?

You might want to check the ChangeLog.  The number of changes have
been large.  Jeff wasted no time in beefing up the IDL compiler after
1.2.1.  Go jeff!  :-)

-Ossama
